---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PaintLab from '../components/PaintLab3D.astro';
import { pageSeo } from '../seo/pages.js';
import { buildWebApplicationJsonLd } from '../seo/meta.js';
import { siteStats } from '../data/site-meta.js';

const seo = pageSeo.paintLab;
const paintLabJsonLd = buildWebApplicationJsonLd({
	name: 'MECCHA CHAMELEON Paint Hide and Seek Simulator',
	description: seo.description,
	path: '/camouflage-simulator',
	dateModified: siteStats.lastVerified,
});
---

<BaseLayout
	title={seo.title}
	description={seo.description}
	keywords={seo.keywords}
	jsonLd={paintLabJsonLd}
>
	<div class="PaintLabPage">
		<section class="inner-hero-section"><div class="container"><div class="inner-hero-content">
			<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><ol class="breadcrumb-list"><li><a href="/">Home</a></li><li><span aria-current="page">Paint Hide and Seek Simulator</span></li></ol></nav>
			<span class="section-label">Practice Simulator · 3D Surface Edition</span><h1>MECCHA CHAMELEON Paint Hide and Seek Simulator</h1>
			<p class="page-intro">A browser-based paint hide and seek simulator for MECCHA CHAMELEON. Choose a preset or uploaded background, drag the figure to any corner of the scene, rotate to inspect the silhouette, then paint directly onto the surface to practise colour, shadow, and edge detail.</p>
			<div class="inner-hero-meta"><span>Drag, rotate & paint</span><span>Browser-local uploads</span><span>No account required</span></div>
		</div></div></section>
		<section class="inner-content-section"><div class="container"><PaintLab /></div></section>
		<section class="inner-content-section is-alt"><div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block is-wide">
			<h2>Use it as a paint hide and seek drill</h2>
			<p>The simulator works best when you test one visual decision at a time. Set the scene first, inspect the silhouette from a likely Seeker angle, then paint broad planes before refining edges.</p>
			<table class="inner-data-table"><thead><tr><th>Practice pass</th><th>What to do</th><th>What to look for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1. Place the scene</td><td>Choose or upload a background and fit or position it behind the figure.</td><td>Does the scene give you one readable surface to hide against?</td></tr><tr><td>2. Move the figure</td><td>Switch to <strong>Move</strong> and drag the figure to any corner or spot on the scene.</td><td>Does the figure sit where a Hider would actually commit to a hide?</td></tr><tr><td>3. Inspect the silhouette</td><td>Switch to <strong>Rotate</strong> and look at the head, torso, arms, and legs from the likely Seeker angle.</td><td>Which body planes are most likely to break the outline?</td></tr><tr><td>4. Paint the surface</td><td>Switch to <strong>Paint</strong>, cover a broad plane first, then add restrained darker or lighter marks.</td><td>Do the colours and surface finish hold together as the figure rotates?</td></tr><tr><td>5. Review honestly</td><td>Reset and try one alternative position, background, or two-colour approach.</td><td>Which change—placement, scene, broad colour, or edge treatment—made the largest difference?</td></tr></tbody></table>
		</div></div></section>
		<section class="inner-content-section" aria-labelledby="method-title"><div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block">
			<h2 id="method-title">What this tool helps you practise</h2>
			<p>The tool focuses on visual fundamentals that transfer to hide-and-seek games: choose a local backdrop, reduce a hard outline, and use restrained colour variation. Use it to practise colour grouping, scene framing, brush restraint, and the way a silhouette reads against a background.</p>
			<ul><li><strong>Practise:</strong> figure placement, colour grouping, scene framing, brush restraint, and silhouette reading.</li><li><strong>Bring your own background:</strong> upload a screenshot or image, position the scene, drag the figure into place, then paint to fit.</li><li><strong>Take it into a round:</strong> pair the exercise with <a href="/wiki#wiki-maps">current map knowledge</a>, <a href="/updates">patch notes</a>, and your room’s rules.</li></ul>
			<p>For game facts, read the <a href="/wiki">Wiki</a> and <a href="/updates">patch archive</a>. For stage-specific practice, start with the <a href="/wiki#wiki-maps">official map notes</a>.</p>
		</div></div></section>
		<section class="inner-content-section is-alt" aria-labelledby="privacy-title"><div class="container"><div class="inner-content-block is-wide">
			<h2 id="privacy-title">Privacy, images, and export</h2>
			<table class="inner-data-table"><thead><tr><th>Action</th><th>How it is handled</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Upload a background</td><td>The selected image is read by your browser for the current canvas session. This page does not send it to a server.</td></tr><tr><td>Move or scale a background</td><td>Position and scale are applied only to the in-browser canvas until you refresh, clear the background, or close the page.</td></tr><tr><td>Move or rotate the figure</td><td>Figure position and rotation stay in the local canvas session. Use <strong>Center figure</strong> to reset placement.</td></tr><tr><td>Paint the figure</td><td>Brush strokes remain in the local canvas session. Reset clears them from the current canvas.</td></tr><tr><td>Save PNG</td><td>The browser creates a PNG from the visible canvas. Review your chosen background before sharing an export.</td></tr></tbody></table>
			<p>Do not upload private, copyrighted, or sensitive images unless you have the right to use them. Review your export before sharing it publicly.</p>
		</div></div></section>
	</div>
</BaseLayout>
